(269, 1418, 'en', 'description', '<p>When exposed to laser marking&nbsp;radiation, most plastics react by developing a mark. The type of mark achieved depends on the type of reaction initiated by the laser &ndash; typically melting, foaming(?) or bleaching. That reaction depends on the composition and colour of the base material. To enhance/modify the colour change, additives may be used.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Used extensively in many chemical marking applications Electrox recommends the following laser marking systems from its extensive range:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.electrox.com/products/raptor-fibre-laser">Raptor Fibre&nbsp;Laser Marker</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://www.electrox.com/products/scorpion-rapide-fibre-laser">Scorpion Fibre Laser Marker</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://electrox.oxygen-test.co.uk/products/cobra-uv-laser">Cobra UV Laser Marker</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Examples of&nbsp;Chemical Marking&nbsp;in industry</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://electrox.oxygen-test.co.uk/applications/automotive">Electrical Panel Cover&nbsp;(Automotive)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://electrox.oxygen-test.co.uk/applications/electronic-devices">Micro Switch&nbsp;(Electronic Devices)</a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href="http://electrox.oxygen-test.co.uk/applications/white-goods">Domestic&nbsp;Appliances&nbsp;(White Goods)</a></p>\r\n'),
